        <h4>Process</h4>
        <p>This field <strong>MUST</strong> be present.</p>
        <p>`dpv:Process` is a concept that represents a process or 'unit' for combining relevant details such as purposes, processing, personal data categories, recipients, and so on. Instances of `dpv:Process` can be used to differentiate between information regarding processing - such as where different purposes are used or that lead to different recipients. Such instances can also be nested within other instances to create a 'modular' structuring of processing activities.</p>
        <div class="note" title="Benefits of using `dpv:Process`">
            <p>Following the [[ISO-27560]] model requires creating a concept called 'purposes' and to utilise an array or a list to hold the associated 'purpose' instances. Given that DPV prefers a strict taxonomy expressed in a graph representation, following the same model would lead to non-intuitive structures. Further, other similar lists such as those for 'pii_type' also require creation of new concepts to represent groups or collections of the actual intended concepts.</p>
        </div>
        <aside class="example" title="Example using Personal Data Handling">
                <p>A single instance of Personal Data Handling:</p>
                <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:Marketing",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:EmailAddress"
    }
}</code></pre>
                <p>Using multiple instances of Personal Data Handling to separate purposes and associated personal data:</p>
                <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:PaymentManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:EmailAddress"
    },
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:IdentityVerification",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:OfficialID"
    }
}</code></pre>
                <p>Using nested instances of Personal Data Handling to separate purposes and associated personal data within the larger instance. In this case, the processing activity is for the same purpose, but the personal data are being sent to different recipients. Alternatively, the same information could have been repeated within each instance to avoid nesting:</p>
                <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:PaymentManagement",
        "dpv:hasProcess": {
            "@type": "dpv:Process",
            "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:EmailAddress",
            "dpv:hasRecipient": "ex:CompanyA"
        },
        "dpv:hasProcess": {
            "@type": "dpv:Process",
            "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:IdentityVerification",
            "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:OfficialID",
            "dpv:hasRecipient": "ex:CompanyB"
        }
    }
}</code></pre>
            </aside>

        <h4>Purpose</h4>
        <p>This field <strong>MUST</strong> be present.</p>
            <p>The purpose of processing personal data, expressed in DPV using <code>hasPurpose</code> as an instance of <code>Purpose</code>.</p>
            <p>[[ISO-27560]] has an additional field called 'purpose_type' that describes the category of the purpose. This is expressed using `skos:broader`. For additional information, such as descriptions, relevant DCT relations should be used.</p>
            <aside class="note" title="Distinction between type and category">
              <p>In RDF and semantic web, the type of a concept is a fundamental assertion as to what that concept it. Such 'types' are expected to never change. It is expressed by using `rdf:type`. We can consider the 'category' of a concept as a grouping or categorisation of that concept amongst other concepts of the same type. E.g. the 'type' is Purpose and the category can be Marketing or Service Provision. To represent categories, we use the `skos:broader` relation from [SKOS].</p>
              <p>For more information on the semantics and modelling of information using DPV, please refer to the [PRIMER].</p>
            </aside>
            <div class="note" title="Interpreting multiple purposes within a single context">
                <p>Where multiple purposes are present within the same or single context, for example the consent record or a personal data handling instance, the interpretation is that they are all applicable for that context. For example, if a personal data handling instance contains 3 purposes - then it is presumed that the consent is for carrying out each of the 3 purposes.</p>
                <p>To declare that ALL purposes must occur together i.e. they cannot be carried out independently, the appropriate semantic relations should be used to express this information - for e.g. by declaring the 3 required purposes as the 'type' for a new combined purpose.</p>
                <p>Caution is advised when modelling consent as jurisdictional requirements such as those from GDPR e.g. Recital 32 states "Consent should cover all processing activities carried out for the same purpose or purposes. When the processing has multiple purposes, consent should be given for all of them.". This means all purposes listed within a record pertaining to a single consent are to be used with that single consent as the legal basis.</p>
            </div>
            <aside class="example" title="Example specifying Purpose">
                <p>Specifying the purpose with type based on the DPV Purpose taxonomy and a description</p>
                <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": {
            "@type": "dpv:Purpose",
            "skos:broader": "dpv:Marketing",
            "dct:description": "Sending newsletters to the customer"
        },
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:EmailAddress"
    }
}</code></pre>
                <p>Specifying multiple purposes with separate types to indicate they both are applicable independently</p>
                <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": {
            "@type": "dpv:Purpose",
            "skos:broader": "dpv:Marketing",
            "dct:description": "Sending newsletters to the customer"
        },
        "dpv:hasPurpose": {
            "@type": "dpv:CommunicationManagement"
        },
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:EmailAddress"
    }
}</code></pre>
                <p>Specifying a combined purpose with multiple types to indicate the purpose is required for all indicated categories:</p>
                <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": {
            "@type": "dpv:Purpose",
            "skos:broader": [ "dpv:Marketing", "dpv:CommunicationManagement" ],
            "dct:description": "Sending newsletters to the customer"
        },
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:EmailAddress"
    }
}</code></pre>
            </aside>

        <h4>Personal Data</h4>
            <p>This field <strong>MUST</strong> be present.</p>
            <p>The personal data ('pii information' in [[ISO-27560]]) involved in processing activities, associated using <code>dpv:hasPersonalData</code> and instances of <code>dpv:PersonalData</code>.</p>
            <p>In [[ISO-27560]], the personal data fields are used to describe aspects of personal data as - type, identifier, optionality, being sensitive and being special category. In the DPV implementation, these are described as annotations or additional relations over the personal data instance.</p>
            <h5>Personal Data Type</h5>
            <p>This field <strong>MUST</strong> be present.</p>
            <p>The type or category of personal data ('pii type' in [[ISO-27560]]), expressed in DPV using `skos:broader`, and optionally using concepts from the [[PD]] taxonomy. The value for this field must use a data category from DPV either through an explicit declaration i.e. using `skos:broader` or through an implicit definition e.g. [[PD]] taxonomy. </p>
            <aside class="example" title="Example specifying personal data and its type">
                <p>Personal data specified using [[PD]] concept</p>
                <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:EmailAddress"
    }
}</code></pre>
                <p>Personal data specified with type explicitly declared using [[PD]] concept. The benefit of this approach is that it enables additional annotations such as a description of the data, as well as associating identifiers with the data category.</p>
                <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": {
            "@type": "dpv:PersonalData",
            "skos:broader": "pd:EmailAddress",
            "dct:description": "The customer's email address"
        }
    }
}</code></pre>
            </aside>
            <h5>Personal Data Identifier</h5>
            <p>This field MAY be present.</p>
            <p>The identifier representing the data values or instances e.g. within a database, expressed in DPV using <code>dct:identifier</code>. </p>
            <aside class="example" title="Example specifying identifier of personal data">
                <p>Here, the identifier refers to a row ID within some internal database. The use of identifier in this case is to avoid exposing the actual email address within the consent record.</p>
                <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": {
            "@type": "dpv:PersonalData",
            "skos:broader": "pd:EmailAddress",
            "dct:identifier": "MDA5-hashed-email-address"
        }
    }
}</code></pre>
            </aside>
            <h5>Personal Data Necessity</h5>
            <p>This field MAY be present.</p>
            <p>The necessity or optionality of this data ('pii optional' in [[ISO-27560]]) for the processing, expressed in DPV using <code>hasNecessity</code> and one of the provided instances of <code>Necessity</code>. If this field is absent, it should be inferred as the data being necessary.</p>
            <aside class="example" title="Example specifying identifier of personal data">
                <p>Here, the identifier refers to a row ID within some internal database. The use of identifier in this case is to avoid exposing the actual email address within the consent record.</p>
                <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": [{
            "@type": "dpv:PersonalData",
            "skos:broader": "pd:EmailAddress",
            "dpv:hasNecessity": "dpv:Required"
        }, {
            "@type": "@type": "dpv:PersonalData",
            "skos:broader": "pd:Name",
            "dpv:hasNecessity": "dpv:Optional"
        }]
    }
}</code></pre>
                <p>Necessity (or Optionality) can also be expressed at broader contexts, such as for the entire personal data handling instance. This has the advantage over [[ISO-27560]] in that some purpose or processing could also be stated to be necessary or optional. In such cases, the expressed necessity is to be applied to ALL concepts within that instance. In the below example, the first instance has both purpose (communication) and personal data (email) as required or necessary, and the second has both (marketing, name) as optional.</p>
                <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasNecessity": "dpv:Required",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:CommunicationManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:EmailAddress"
    }, {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasNecessity": "dpv:Optional",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:Marketing",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:Name"
    }]
}</code></pre>
                <p>In the absence of a necessity statement, the default interpretation should be that the necessity is <code>dpv:Required</code>. In the below example, both instances have the necessity required even when only one of them explicitly declares it. As good practice, it is always better to specify the necessity explicitly to avoid confusion.</p>
                <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasNecessity": "dpv:Required",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:CommunicationManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:EmailAddress"
    }, {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:Marketing",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:Name"
    }]
}</code></pre>
            </aside>
            <h5>Sensitive and Special Category</h5>
            <p>This field MAY be present.</p>
            <p>Indicates whether the personal data is considered sensitive ('sensitive pii category' in [[ISO-27560]]), and separately whether it is also of special category ('special pii category' in [[ISO-27560]]). Declaring either in DPV is done using `skos:broader` with value <code>SensitivePersonalData</code> or <code>SpecialCategoryPersonalData</code>. Its absence indicates the data does not belong to either sensitive or special categories.</p>
            <aside class="example" title="Example specifying personal data belonging to sensitive and special categories">
                <p>Being sensitive or special category is equivalent to defining it as the 'type' of data in DPV. Therefore, the notation for declaring type and sensitive is the same. In the below example, the first instance is sensitive, the second of special category, and the third is neither.</p>
                <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": [{
            "@type": "dpv:SensitivePersonalData",
            "skos:broader": "pd:Location",
            "dct:identifier": "The user's real-time GPS location"
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:SpecialCategoryPersonalData",
            "skos:broader": "pd:MedicalHealth",
            "dct:identifier": "The user's health records from their local GP"
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:PersonalData",
            "@skos:broader": "pd:Email",
            "dct:identifier": "The user's provided email address"
        }]
    }
}</code></pre>
            </aside>

        <h4>Processing Operations</h4>
        <p>This field <strong>MAY</strong> be present.</p>
        <p>Indicates the processing operations or activities carried out over the specific personal data, and indicated using <code>dpv:hasProcessing</code> with instances of <code>dpv:Processing</code>. In [[ISO-27560]], this field also represents information about automated decision making - which is represented in DPV through the <code>dpv:AutomationOfProcessing</code> concepts and associated with <code>dpv:hasProcessingAutomation</code>, as well as large scale of processing which is represented through <code>dpv:ScaleOfProcessing</code> and associated using <code>dpv:hasScale</code>.</p>

        <aside class="example" title="Example specifying processing operations over personal data">
            <p>Processing operations specified by using the DPV taxonomy, and associated with personal data and purposes using <code>PersonalDataHandling</code>. In this example, the email address is collected, stored, and used.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:CommunicationManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:EmailAddress",
        "dpv:hasProcessing": ["dpv:Collect", "dpv:Store", "dpv:Use"]
    }]
}</code></pre>
            <p>Processing specified with automated decision making, profiling, and large scale of processing. In DPV, profiling is a processing operation, whereas automated decision making and scale of processing are separate concepts.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:CommunicationManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:EmailAddress",
        "dpv:hasProcessing": ["dpv:Collect", "dpv:Store", "dpv:Use"],
        "dpv:hasProcessingAutomation": "dpv:FullyAutomatedProcessing",
        "dpv:hasScale": "dpv:LargeScaleProcessing"
    }]
}</code></pre>
            <p>Another similar example to showcase the range of processing context concepts in DPV - here the processing is highly automated decision making with human involvement, and involves a small scale of processing for a large scale of data subjects.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:CommunicationManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:EmailAddress",
        "dpv:hasProcessing": ["dpv:Collect", "dpv:Store", "dpv:Use", "dpv:Profiling"],
        "dpv:hasProcessingAutomation": "dpv:HighAutomation",
        "dpv:hasHumanInvolvement": "dpv:HumanInvolvementForOversight",
        "dpv:hasScale": ["dpv:SmallScaleProcessing", "dpv:LargeScaleOfDataSubjects"]
    }]
}</code></pre>
            <p>Another similar example with more specific associations between processing operations and contextual information such as full automation, large scale, and no human involvement.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:CommunicationManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": pd:EmailAddress",
        "dpv:hasProcessing": [{
            "@type": "dpv:Processing",
            "skos:broader": "dpv:Use",
            "dpv:hasScale": ["dpv:LargeScaleProcessing", "dpv:LargeScaleOfDataSubjects"],
            "dpv:hasProcessingAutomation": "dpv:FullAutomation",
            "dpv:hasHumanInvolvement": "dpv:HumanNotInvolved"
        }]
    }]
}</code></pre>
        </aside>

        <h5>Data Source(s)</h5>
        <p>This field MAY be present.</p>
        <p>This field represents the source of data being processed. In [[ISO-27560]], this field is called <i>collection method</i> and can be about The data provided by or observed from activities of the data subjects, be inferred from existing data, or be collected from another entity or third party. In DPV, this information is represented using <code>dpv:DataSource</code> and associated using <code>dpv:hasDataSource</code>.</p>
        <p>Concepts within the DPV taxonomy have an exact meaning - for example data being obtained through observation should not be stated as being <i>collected</i>, but as <i>observed</i> - even if the data source is still the same data subject. Therefore, it is best to separate the data source <i>entity</i> and the <i>processing operation</i>.</p>
        <aside class="example" title="Example specifying sources of data used in processing operations">
            <p>The following examples state the data subject as a data source as stated in [[ISO-27560]] for direct data collection, indirect observation or derivation, and inferred.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:CommunicationManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:Location",
        "dpv:hasDataSource": [{
            "@type": "dpv:DataSubjectDataSource",
            "dpv:hasProcessing": "dpv:Collect"
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:DataSubjectDataSource",
            "dpv:hasProcessing": "dpv:Observe"
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:DataSubjectDataSource",
            "dpv:hasProcessing": ["dpv:Collect", "dpv:Derive"],
            "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:IPAddress"
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:DataSubjectDataSource",
            "dpv:hasProcessing": "dpv:Infer",
            "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:BrowserBehavior"
        }
    }]
}</code></pre>
            <p>The following example states non- data subject entities as a data source as stated in [[ISO-27560]], where the entities are of type Processor and Third Party respectively. The example also shows how processing operations can directly specify their data sources.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:CommunicationManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:Location",
        "dpv:hasProcessing": [{
            "@type": "dpv:Processing",
            "skos:broader": dpv:Transfer",
            "dpv:hasDataSource": {
                "@type": "dpv:DataProcessorDataSource",
                "@id": "https://example.com/Acme"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:Processing", 
            "skos:broader": ["dpv:Collect", "dpv:Acquire"],
            "dpv:hasDataSource": {
                "@type": "dpv:ThirdPartyDataSource",
                "@id": "https://example.com/Beta"   
            }
        }]
    }]
}</code></pre>
            <p>The following example shows how data sources can be specified in terms of devices and technologies using concepts from (work-in-progress) [[TECH]].</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:CommunicationManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": pd:Location",
        "dpv:hasDataSource": {
            "@type": "dpv:DataSubjectDataSource",
            "dpv:hasProcessing": "dpv:Collect",
            "dpv:isImplementedUsingTechnology": {
                "@type": "tech:Device",
                "tech:hasCommunicationMechanism": ["tech:GPS", "tech:WiFi"]
            }
        }
    }]
}</code></pre>
</aside>

        <h5>Storage Condition(s)</h5>
        <p>This field <strong>MUST</strong> be present.</p>
        <p>Indicates information about the storage of personal data such as regarding its duration, location, and erasure, represented using <code>dpv:StorageCondition</code> and associated using <code>dpv:hasStorageCondition</code>. The existence of Storage Condition implies storing data as a processing operation. In [[ISO-27560]], this information is represented through two fields - <i>storage locations</i> and <i>retention period</i> - both of which are required to be present.</p>
        <aside class="example" title="Example specifying conditions regarding storage of data in terms of location, duration, and retention">
            <p>The following example shows how information about storage conditions can be associated using the DPV concepts. It associates three conditions with the personal data handling instance representing location, duration, and retention.</p>
            <p>The first example shows locations expressed using the DPV-Locations extension (work in progress), and indicate that data will be stored in Ireland, France, and Germany - with another example showing EU as a (jurisdiction-based) location. The other examples show how non-geopolitical locations can be represented using DPV.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:CommunicationManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": pd:Location",
        "dpv:hasDataStorageCondition": [{
            "@type": "dpv:StorageLocation",
            "dpv:hasLocation": ["loc:IE", "loc:FR", "loc:DE"],
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:StorageLocation",
            "dpv:hasLocation": "loc:EU"
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:StorageLocation",
            "dpv:hasLocation": "dpv:WithinDevice"
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:StorageLocation",
            "dpv:hasLocation": {
                "@type": ["dpv:FederatedLocation", 
                    "dpv:WithinDevice", "dpv:CloudLocation"]
            }
        }]
    }]
}</code></pre>
            <p>The following example shows the duration associated with storage of data. Duration implies that data will be removed or erased after the duration. For date and period durations, there are two examples given where one directly uses the value and the other explicitly specifies the kind of duration.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:CommunicationManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:Location",
        "dpv:hasStorageCondition": [{
            "@type": "dpv:StorageDuration",
            "rdfs:comment": "6 Months using ISO 8601",
            "dpv:hasDuration": "P6M",
            "dpv:hasDuration": {
                "@type": ["dpv:TemporalDuration", "xsd:duration"],
                "rdf:value": "P6M"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:StorageDuration",
            "rdfs:comment": "duration lapsing at the end of year",
            "dpv:hasDuration": "2023-12-31",
            "dpv:hasDuration": {
                "@type": ["dpv:UntilTimeDuration", "xsd:date"],
                "rdf:value": "2023-12-31"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:StorageDuration",
            "dpv:hasDuration": {
                "@type": "dpv:FixedOccurrencesDuration",
                "rdf:value": "12"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:StorageDuration",
            "dpv:hasDuration": {
                "@type": "dpv:UntilEventDuration",
                "rdf:value": "Account Closure"
            }
        }]
    }]
}</code></pre>
            <p>The following example shows erasure as a distinct condition separate from the storage duration. In [[ISO-27560]], the field for <i>retention period</i> refers to both the retention and erasure of data. In DPV, this is separated as data may get scheduled for deletion and may remain stored for a duration before its actual erasure. In the example, the data is to be stored for 6 months and then deleted by 1 month following this period.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:CommunicationManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:Location",
        "dpv:hasStorageCondition": [{
            "@type": "dpv:StorageDuration",
            "dpv:hasDuration": "P6M"
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:StorageDeletion",
            "dpv:hasDuration": "P1M"
        }]
    }]
}</code></pre>
</aside>

        <h5>Processing Condition(s)</h5>
        <p>This field MAY be present.</p>
        <p>Indicates information about conditions regarding the processing operations, such as regarding its duration and location, represented using <code>dpv:ProcessingCondition</code> and associated using <code>dpv:hasProcessingCondition</code>. Given that storing data is a specific type of processing operation, this field is useful for other processing activities such as collection of data. In [[ISO-27560]], the field only relates to <i>processing locations</i>.</p>
        <aside class="example" title="Example specifying conditions regarding processing data in terms of location and duration">
            <p>The examples show various combinations of processing location and duration, using the same concepts and patterns as those used in the examples for Storage Condition. In addition, it also shows the possibility to express the <i>frequency</i> of processing using <code>dpv:Frequency</code> and associated using <code>dpv:hasFrequency</code>. To express combinations of duration, location, and frequencies - their respective concepts can be combined as shown explicitly last example.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:CommunicationManagement",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:Location",
        "dpv:hasDataProcessingCondition": [{
            "@type": "dpv:ProcessingLocation",
            "dpv:hasLocation": "dpv:WithinDevice",
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:ProcessingLocation",
            "dpv:hasLocation": "loc:EU"
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:ProcessingDuration",
            "dpv:hasDuration": "P6M"
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:ProcessingFrequency",
            "dpv:hasFrequency": "dpv:SingularFrequency"
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:ProcessingFrequency",
            "dpv:hasFrequency": "dpv:ContinuousFrequency"
        }, {
            "@type": ["dpv:ProcessingLocation", 
                    "dpv:ProcessingDuration", "dpv:ProcessingFrequency"],
            "dpv:hasLocation": "dpv:WithinDevice",
            "dpv:hasDuration": "P1D",
            "dpv:hasFrequency": "dpv:SporadicFrequency"
        }]
    }]
}</code></pre>
</aside>

        <h5>Geographic Restriction(s)</h5>
        <p>This field MAY be present.</p>
        <p>Geographic restrictions are defined in [[ISO-27560]] as restrictions related to geo-locations or jurisdictions. While DPV prefers a declarative interpretation where, for e.g., if processing location is mentioned as EU then it implies that processing will only take place within EU since no other locations are mentioned. If the intention is to explicitly state this as a restriction, it can utilise the <code>dpv:Rule</code> concept which provides (simplified) Permissions, Prohibitions, and Obligations. For further expressiveness of complexity, specifications such as [[[odrl-model]]] should be considered.</p>
        <p>Note that while [[ISO-27560]] only considers restrictions over geographic locations for processing (including storing), DPV (and ODRL)support specifying information and restrictions over a much wider range of concepts. In theory, restrictions can be expressed over any concept or combination of concepts.</p>
        <aside class="example" title="Example specifying geographic restrictions on the processing of personal data">
            <p>The below example expresses that data must be stored within EU. Note that DPV's concepts do not support expressing negations i.e. we cannot state data must <i>not</i> be stored within <i>non-EU</i> locations. Also note the ambiguity in interpreting DPV's obligation as meaning either data must only be stored in EU or must at least be stored in EU (in addition to elsewhere). An alternative to this is to utilise an appropriate vocabulary such as [[ODRL]] - as in the second rule below, or as a last resort to use plain text - which is less desirable.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasRule": [{
            "@type": "dpv:Obligation",
            "dpv:hasLocation": "loc:EU",
            "dpv:hasProcessing": "dpv:Store",
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:Prohibition",
            "rdfs:comment": "Use ODRL concepts here"
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:Prohibition",
            "dpv:hasProcessing": "dpv:Store",
            "dct:description": "Storing in Non-EU locations is NOT allowed"
        }]
    }
}</code></pre>
</aside>

        <h4>Data Controller(s)</h4>
        <p>This field <strong>MUST</strong> be present.</p>
        <p>Indicates the Data Controllers (pii controllers in [[ISO-27560]]) responsible for the specified processing activities, expressed in DPV  using <code>hasDataController</code> with instances of <code>DataController</code>.</p>
        <p>Note that the notion of a 'Controller' is regarding accountability, and does not necessarily correlate with who performs the processing or has access to data - for example in GDPR. To indicate who performs the processing, DPV provides <code>dpv:isImplementedByEntity</code>.</p>
        <p>Information about the Data Controller, such as its name or address, is described through the <i>Entity Fields</i> later in the document based on a similar structure in [[ISO-27560]].</p>
        <aside class="example" title="Example specifying Data Controllers">
            <p>The below examples show processing where a single entity acts as the data controller for all of the processing (represented using <code>PersonalDataHandling</code>, and extends it to show how  different controllers can be associated for different processing activities.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:IdentityVerification",
        "dpv:hasDataController": "ex:Acme"
    }, {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:ServiceProvision",
        "dpv:hasDataController": "ex:Beta"
    }]
}</code></pre>
            <p>In case of multiple controller, these can be stated as a list of controllers, or - in the case of GDPR - be also declared as a joint controller using <code>dpv:JointDataController</code>.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:IdentityVerification",
        "dpv:hasDataController": ["ex:Acme", "ex:Beta"]
    }
}</code></pre>
</aside>

        <h4>Legal Basis</h4>
            <p>This field MAY be present.</p>
            <p>The legal basis (lawful basis in [[ISO-27560]] for processing of personal data. Though the lawful basis for a consent record would always be consent, the presence of the field enables extensions of the record to other legal bases (e.g. contract) in the future. In DPV, the legal basis is associated using <code>hasLegalBasis</code> with a concept from the <code>LegalBasis</code> taxonomy.</p>
            <p>In addition to defining consent as a legal basis, DPV also provides a taxonomy to express various categories of consent - such as <code>InformedConsent</code> and <code>ExpressedConsent</code> which provide a more granular and accurate definition of the legal basis being utilised. For expressing specific consent based on specific jurisdictions and regulations, the appropriate extended concept should be used, for e.g. [[EU-GDPR]] extension defines consent as a legal basis based on the specific clauses and requirements of the [[GDPR]].</p>
            <aside class="example" title="Example specifying consent as a legal basis">
            <p>Consent is directly associated with the first <code>PersonalDataHandling</code> as the legal basis. Such use is commonly interpreted as meaning consent according to some obligations and requirements to be considered valid, for example being informed and expressed rather than assumed. The second <code>PersonalDataHandling</code> uses the specific type of consent required which clearly indicates which requirements it is expected to fulfil to be considered valid.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasLegalBasis": "dpv:Consent"
    }, {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasLegalBasis": "dpv:ExplicitlyExpressedConsent"
    }]
}</code></pre>
        <p>To indicate that a GDPR-defined consent is being used as the legal basis, the [[EU-GDPR]] concept is used by itself or in combination with a core consent type to explicitly indicate the level of consent. Note that in the second example, [[EU-GDPR]] already defines <code>A9-2-a</code> as a subtype of <code>dpv:ExplicitlyExpressedConsent</code>, so the combined use does not lead to contradictions.</p>
        <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasLegalBasis": "eu-gdpr:A6-1-a"
    }, {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasLegalBasis": ["dpv:ExplicitlyExpressedConsent", "eu-gdpr:A9-2-a"]
    }]
}</code></pre>
</aside>
        
        <h4>Recipients</h4>
        <p>This field <strong>MUST</strong> be present.</p>
        <p>Indicates the recipients of personal data associated with the specific processing activities, expressed as <code>dpv:Recipient</code> and associated using <code>dpv:hasRecipient</code>. In [[ISO-27560]], this field is only limited to Recipients who are Third Parties, which excludes the Data Controllers and Processors. In DPV, recipients can be any of Data Controllers, or Processors, or Third Parties.</p>
        <p>Note that recipients can be specific entities i.e. their identity is known, or groups or categories of entities - for example as in GDPR's Article 13-1e. However, [[ISO-27560]] only considered explicitly indicated third parties for the recipients field.</p>
        <p>In [[ISO-27560]], the recipient field is also associated with information regarding the geo-location of data being transferred to the recipient third party's and whether this constitutes a jurisdictional change. To represent this in DPV, the location of the transfer should be indicated within the processing information along with the recipient entity. The jurisdiction can also be represented in the same context - to indicate the transfer to that jurisdiction, or it can be specified in association with the recipient entity.</p>
        <aside class="example" title="Example specifying recipients of personal data">
            <p>Recipients can be indicated separately for the entirety of <code>PersonalDataHandling</code> which indicates all data is being received by the specified recipient.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": ["pd:Email", "pd:Name"],
        "dpv:hasDataController": "ex:Acme",
        "dpv:hasRecipient": "ex:Beta"
    }
}</code></pre>
            <p>Recipients can be also be indicated contextually within each <code>PersonalDataHandling</code> or <code>Processing</code> to indicate the recipient entity for that specific context - which allows to separate the recipients based on what data and processing they are associated with. In the below example, the first activity has Acme receiving the Email, and the second activity has Beta collecting the Name and transferring it to Gamma.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:Email",
        "dpv:hasRecipient": "ex:Acme"
    }, {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:Name",
        "dpv:hasProcessing": [{
            "@type": "dpv:Collect",
            "dpv:hasRecipient": "ex:Beta"
        }, {
            "@type": "dpv:Transfer",
            "dpv:hasRecipient": "ex:Gamma"
        }
    }
}</code></pre>
            <p>To specify the locations and jurisdictions of recipients, the appropriate DPV concepts and relations are used. In the below example, the first activity states Acme is a Recipient and also the Data Controller whose location is Ireland, and the second activity states that the transfer to Beta has location France and jurisdiction EU.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": [{
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:Email",
        "dpv:hasDataController": "ex:Acme",
        "dpv:hasRecipient": {
            "@type": "dpv:Recipient",
            "@id": "ex:Acme",
            "dpv:hasLocation": "loc:IE"
        }
    }, {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPersonalData": "pd:Name",
        "dpv:hasProcessing": {
            "@type": "dpv:Transfer",
            "dpv:hasRecipient": "ex:Beta",
            "dpv:hasLocation": "loc:France",
            "dpv:hasJurisdiction": "loc:EU"
        }
    }]
}</code></pre>
</aside>
        
        <h4>Consent Change &amp; Withdrawal</h4>
            <p>This field <strong>MUST</strong> be present.</p>
            <div class="issue" data-number="115"></div>
            <p>Indicates the information on how the data subject can change or withdraw the specified consent. This is done by expressing information using `dpv:ConsentControl` and `dpv:hasConsentControl`. DPV provides specific involvement controls for consent as `dpv:ProvideConsent`, `dpv:WithdrawConsent`, `dpv:ObtainConsent`, and `dpv:ReaffirmConsent`. To indicate how the data subject should take action, the relation <code>isExercisedAt</code> is to be used.</p>
            <p>In [[ISO-27560]], this field is specific to the withdrawal method or a link to the information on withdrawal. It also allows this field to be associated with the Data Controller (in the Party/Entity section) rather than per-processing activity.</p>
            
            <aside class="example" title="Example specifying change and withdrawal of consent">
            <p>To express how the data subject can withdraw consent.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasConsentControl": {
            "@type": "dpv:WithdrawConsent",
            "dpv:isExercisedAt": "https://example.com/manage-consent"
        }
    }
}</code></pre>
            <p>To express how the data subject can provide, access or view, confirm or reaffirm, change, or withdraw their consent using a single link.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasConsentControl": {
            "@type": [
                "dpv:ProvideConsent", 
                "dpv:WithdrawConsent", 
                "dpv:ReaffirmConsent"],
            "dpv:isExercisedAt": "https://example.com/manage-consent"
        }
    }
}</code></pre>
</aside>

        <h4>Jurisdiction(s)</h4>
            <p>This field <strong>MUST</strong> be present.</p>
            <p>Indicates the applicable jurisdiction for the processing indicated within the receipt. The acknowledgement of jurisdiction(s) is necessary to convey applicable laws and requirements regarding consent validity and applicable rights as well as indicating the obligations on parties involved. To indicate the jurisdiction, the concept <code>Location</code> is to be associated using <code>hasJurisdiction</code>. The [[LOC]] extension can be used for this which provides a list of locations based on ISO-3166.mm</p>
            <p>In [[ISO-27560]], this field can also be associated with the Data Controller (in the Party/Entity section) rather than per-processing activity.</p>

            <aside class="example" title="Example specifying jurisdiction">
            <p>To express how the data subject can withdraw consent.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasJurisdiction": "loc:EU"
    }
}</code></pre>
</aside>

        <h4>Rights</h4>
        <p>This field <strong>MUST</strong> be present.</p>
        <p>Indicates the applicable rights and provides information on how to avail or exercise them. The rights are indicated using <code>DataSubjectRight</code> and associated using <code>hasRight</code>. To indicate how to exercise them, the relation <code>isExercisedAt</code> is to be used. To indicate provision of information regarding rights exercise, the concept <code>RightExerciseNotice</code> is to be used and associated using <code>hasNotice</code>.</p>
        <p>In [[ISO-27560]], this field is <i>optional</i>, and is used to provide a link to information on how to exercise rights. It also allows this field to allow changes to the consent conditions such as the retention period. In [[ISO-27560]], this field can also be associated with the Data Controller (in the Party/Entity section) rather than per-processing activity.</p>
        <aside class="example" title="Example specifying rights exercise information">
            <p>Expressing rights exercise information using DPV is done using the <code>DataSubjectRight</code> instance and associated using <code>hasRight</code>. The contents of this information can include annotations, such as using <code>dct:title</code> to summarise the right, and <code>dpv:isExercisedAt</code> to indicate how/where it is to be exercised.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasRight": {
            "@type": "dpv:DataSubjectRight",
            "dct:title": "Right to Obtain Information",
            "dct:description": "To obtain information, go to the specified link",
            "dpv:isExercisedAt": "https://example.com/rights"
        }
    }
}</code></pre>
            <p>To indicate specific rights under a particular jurisdiction or regulation, the appropriate concepts have to be declared and used. In this example, GDPR's Right to Withdraw Consent (Art.7-3) and Right to Data Portability (Art.20) are described with information on how to exercise them. This can be done with explicit acknowledgement of GDPR as the regulation using <code>dpv:hasApplicableLaw</code>, and EU as the jurisdiction using <code>hasJurisdiction</code>.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasRight": [{
            "@type": ["dpv:DataSubjectRight", "eu-gdpr:A7-3"],
            "dct:title": "Right to Withdraw Consent",
            "dpv:isExercisedAt": "https://example.com/rights",
            "dpv:hasApplicableLaw": "eu-gdpr:GDPR",
            "dpv:hasJurisdiction": "loc:EU"
        }, {
            "@type": ["dpv:DataSubjectRight", "eu-gdpr:A20"],
            "dct:title": "Right to Data Portability",
            "dpv:isExercisedAt": "https://example.com/rights",
            "dpv:hasApplicableLaw": "eu-gdpr:GDPR",
            "dpv:hasJurisdiction": "loc:EU"
        }]
    }
}</code></pre>
            <p>The same or similar right can be applicable under multiple jurisdictions and/or regulations. In this example, the Right to Withdraw Consent is expressed as being applicable under multiple jurisdictions using <code>hasJurisdiction</code>.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasRight": {
            "@type": "dpv:DataSubjectRight",
            "dct:title": "Right to Withdraw Consent",
            "dpv:isExercisedAt": "https://example.com/rights",
            "dpv:hasJurisdiction": ["loc:EU", "loc:EEA"]
        }
    }
}</code></pre>
            <p>To indicate information required for exercise of rights, DPV's existing properties such as <code>hasPersonalData</code> and necessity concepts such as <code>Required</code> can be used. This example shows the right to data portability requires collecting an email for exercising it.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasRight": {
            "@type": ["dpv:DataSubjectRight", "eu-gdpr:A20"],
            "dct:title": "Right to Data Portability",
            "dpv:isExercisedAt": "https://example.com/rights",
            "dpv:hasProcess": {
                "@type": "dpv:Process",
                "dpv:hasPersonalData": "dpv:Email",
                "dpv:hasProcessing": "dpv:Collect",
                "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:FulfilmentOfObligation",
                "dpv:hasNecessity": "dpv:Required"
} } } }</code></pre>
            <p>To indicate what will be the resulting action from exercising the right, existing concepts and external vocabularies such as schema.org or DCAT can be used. This example shows the resulting obligation from exercising the right to data portability being the provision of a dataset containing collected personal data.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasRight": {
            "@type": ["dpv:DataSubjectRight", "eu-gdpr:A20"],
            "dct:title": "Right to Data Portability",
            "dpv:isExercisedAt": "https://example.com/rights",
            "dpv:hasProcess": {
                "@type": "dpv:Process",
                "dpv:hasPersonalData": "dpv:Email",
                "dpv:hasProcessing": "dpv:Collect",
                "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:FulfilmentOfObligation",
                "dpv:hasNecessity": "dpv:Required"
            },
            "dpv:hasObligation": {
                "@type": "schema:SendAction",
                "schema:recipient": "dpv:DataSubject",
                "schema:object": {
                    "@type": "schema:Dataset",
                    "dpv:hasPersonalData": "dpv:CollectedData",
                    "schema:distribution": {
                        "schema:encodingFormat": "iana:CSV",

} } } } } }</code></pre>
</aside>

        <h4>Service(s)</h4>
            <p>This field <i>MAY</i> be present.
            <p>Indicates the services the described processing activities are a part of or assist with, expressed as an instance of <code>dpv:Service</code> and associated using <code>dpv:hasService</code>.</p>
            <p>In [[ISO-27560]], a Service can be as broad or granular as desired. A service is related to a purpose by providing a context through which the specific purpose can be understood within their context, and also to enable related purposes and activities to be associated and explained with a common service being provided.</p>
            <aside class="example" title="Example specifying service">
            <p>To indicate processing activities are associated with a specific service, an instance of <code>dpv:Service</code> is associated using <code>dpv:hasService</code>. In this example, the expression of a service provides important context for the interpretation of the purpose of <code>dpv:ServiceProvision</code>.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasPurpose": "dpv:ServiceProvision",
        "dpv:hasService": {
            "@type": "dpv:Service",
            "dct:title": "Movie Streaming"
        }
    }
}</code></pre>
</aside>

        <h4>Code of conduct(s)</h4>
        <p>This field MAY be present.</p>
        <p>Indicates the applicability of a <i>Code of Conduct</i> for the specified processing activity. A code of conduct is a voluntary set of rules and responsibilities undertaken by an organisation. It is indicated using an instance of <code>dpv:CodeOfConduct</code> and associated using <code>dpv:hasOrganisationalMeasure</code>.</p>
        <p>In [[ISO-27560]], this field is described as providing information regarding the name of the code of conduct and a publicly accessible reference to it. A code of conduct can also be associated with the Data Controller (in the Party/Entity section) rather than per-processing activity.</p>
        <aside class="example" title="Example specifying Code of Conduct">
            <p>To express the code of conduct applicable to processing.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasOrganisationalMeasure": {
            "@type": "dpv:OrganisationalMeasure",
            "skos:broader": "dpv:CodeOfConduct",
            "dct:title": "Code of Conduct on Processing Personal Data",
            "schema:url": "https://example.com/CoC"
        }
    }
}</code></pre>
</aside>

        <h4>Impact assessment(s)</h4>
        <p>This field MAY be present.</p>
        <p>Indicates the existence of an <i>Impact Assessment</i> for the specified processing activity. An impact assessment in this record refers to the impact of the specified processing activities on the data subject. Impact assessments are indicated using instances of <code>dpv:ImpactAssessment</code> and associated using <code>dpv:hasAssessment</code>. DPV provides concepts for specific types of impact assessments, such as <code>dpv:PIA</code> for Privacy Impact Assessment and <code>dpv:DPIA</code> for Data Protection Impact Assessment.</p>
        <p>In [[ISO-27560]], this field is limited to assessments of privacy risks and potential impacts of "non-compliance" on the data subjects, whereas in common practice assessments such as PIA and DPIA concern the impact of the processing on the data subject - which is what DPV and this specification considers. Impact assessments can also be associated with the Data Controller (in the Party/Entity section) rather than per-processing activity.</p>
        <aside class="example" title="Example specifying impact assessment">
            <p>To express an impact assessment applicable for the processing.</p>
            <pre><code>{
    "@id": "https://example.com/a6f58318-72e6-46a2-bfd7-f36d795e30cd",
    "@type": "dpv:ConsentRecord",
    "dpv:hasProcess": {
        "@type": "dpv:Process",
        "dpv:hasAssessment": {
            "@type": "dpv:DPIA",
            "schema:url": "https://example.com/DPIA"
        }
    }
}</code></pre>
</aside>

    <h3>Entity Fields</h3>
    <p>[[ISO-27560]] refers to <i>Entity</i> as <i>Party</i>.</p>
    <p>Entities are expressed using instances of <code>dpv:Entity</code> and associated using <code>dpv:hasEntity</code>.</p>
    <table style="font-family: monospace;">
    <thead>
        <tr>
            <th>Field</th>
            <th>Cardinality</th>
            <th>DPV Concept</th>
            <th>DPV Property</th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <th>Name</th>
            <td>1..*</td>
            <td>N/A</td>
            <td><a href="https://w3id.org/dpv#hasName">dpv:hasName</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <th>Identifier</th>
